						<p>UN-Habitat, in collaboration with the Cities Coalition for Digital Rights, Eurocities and United Cities and Local Governments (UCLG) with funding from the Open Society Foundations, has launched the technical report: Human Rights in the Digital Era – Learnings on local governance from pilots in Europe with outcomes and tools developed as part of the Digital Rights Governance Project in Europe.</p>
						<p>The project team worked with local governments in Brussels, Dublin, Sofia and Tirana, and focused on technical support to uphold people-centered digital transformation strategies, policies and projects anchored on the promotion and protection of human rights in the digital context of cities.</p>
						<p>Digital transformation in cities and human settlements is complex and requires leadership, effective governance, capacity and a strong commitment to human rights, inclusion and sustainability. There are many opportunities to harness the potential of digital solutions for sustainable urban development; they have the potential to improve access to education, affordable housing, and critical government services. But there are also risks, challenges and unintended consequences if these technologies are not well governed.</p>
